# 64_app_gtk_version_smoke — second verb on the `app` headless-verb
# singleton (s263 m3). Verb-on-existing-singleton; no Tier 4 row tick
# (the row ticked 2 → 3 at s263 m2 when AppScriptable opened with the
# `version` verb; this smoke validates the second pure-read verb
# `gtk_version` added in the same delivery as a stretch milestone).
#
# `app gtk_version` reports the RUNTIME gtkmm version — the GTK
# library actually loaded by the dynamic linker at process start.
# Distinct from `app version` which reports the BUILD-TIME Curvz
# identity (CURVZ_VERSION macro from CMake's project(curvz VERSION)).
# For bug reports, both numbers are needed to characterise the
# environment: build version names "which Curvz" the user is running,
# runtime gtk version names "which GTK that Curvz is sitting on."
# These can diverge on a system where the user updated their distro's
# GTK without rebuilding Curvz against the new headers.
#
# ── What this smoke exercises ─────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# `app gtk_version` has the same one-case contract as `app version`
# (see AppScriptable.hpp for the full design block):
#
#   Branch A (happy path):  always. Returns
#                           "<major>.<minor>.<micro>" via
#                           gtk_get_major_version() /
#                           gtk_get_minor_version() /
#                           gtk_get_micro_version() — C-level
#                           functions guaranteed initialised by
#                           GTK's own startup before main().
#   Branch B (extra args):  any positional argument is a misuse.
#                           Refuses with "app gtk_version: expected
#                           zero arguments".
#
# Unlike smoke 63's assertable build-version string (CURVZ_VERSION is
# baked at compile time, so the smoke knows what value to expect),
# the runtime GTK version varies by system — Scott's Fedora aarch64
# build will report a different micro than a Flathub manifest's
# bundled GTK, which will differ from a future MSYS2 Windows port.
# The smoke does NOT assert on the value because the listener's
# substring-match primitive doesn't exist yet; once it does, a
# `starts_with` assertion against "4." would be the right shape
# (Curvz's minimum-required GTK is 4.x; the major version is the
# only thing the smoke can portably know without per-system
# configuration). Operator-visual on the trace's echoed value.
#
# This smoke runs Branch A (operator-visual only, no assertion),
# plus the argument-count refusal (Branch B), plus an unknown-verb
# refusal on the same singleton. Three observable lines, zero
# assertions.
#
# ── Caller context ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Same as smoke 63: ScripterWindow listener, RunContext::Scripter.
# `app gtk_version` declares its mask as Scripter | TestRunner
# (Macro is OUT — recorded-macro replay on a system with a different
# distro's GTK means the recorded value is stale at replay time,
# violating the recorded-macro mental model). Eleventh consumer of
# Scriptable::context_mask() in the codebase (Inspector + 5 proj
# verbs + 2 export verbs + 2 app verbs).
#
# ── Test isolation ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Pure read with no side effects. Same shape as smoke 63's isolation
# posture — safe to run anywhere any time, idempotent across repeated
# calls.
#
# ── Predicted observables ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Expected summary line at smoke close:
#
#   4 lines, 0 pass, 0 fail, 2 error
#
# - 1 "ok" line from `app gtk_version` happy-path call (Phase 1).
# - 1 "ok" line from a re-call confirming idempotence (Phase 2).
# - 1 "error" line from extra-args refusal (Phase 3).
# - 1 "error" line from unknown-verb refusal (Phase 4).
#
# Same conservative-smoke shape as smoke 60 (1-verb, 2-refusal),
# but with the verb called twice across two phases instead of
# wrapping a single call in an assertion (no assertable value, so
# the structural validation is "the second call returns the same
# echo as the first" — operator-visual). Identical line count to
# smoke 63 (4); zero passes because there's no assertion. The pass
# count difference between 63 and 64 (1 vs 0) is the only structural
# difference between the two smokes; otherwise their shape is
# identical.

#[sub] === Phase 1: app gtk_version (Branch A — happy path) ===

#[sub] Call the verb. The expected trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   > app gtk_version
#[sub]   ok "<major>.<minor>.<micro>"
#[sub]
#[sub] e.g. "4.14.5" on Scott's Fedora aarch64 build. Operator-visual
#[sub] on the `ok` echo and the version string format. The exact
#[sub] number depends on the system's GTK install; the smoke can't
#[sub] assert on it without a substring-match primitive that doesn't
#[sub] exist yet (future milestone — `assert app gtk_version
#[sub] starts_with "4."` would be the right shape).

app gtk_version

#[sub] === Phase 2: idempotence — call the verb again ===

#[sub] The runtime GTK version doesn't change during a Curvz session
#[sub] (GTK is loaded once at process start; the dynamic linker
#[sub] doesn't swap libraries mid-process). Re-calling the verb
#[sub] should produce the same echo. Operator-visual on the second
#[sub] `ok` line matching the first; this validates the listener's
#[sub] dispatch state wasn't poisoned by the first invoke (same
#[sub] structural property smoke 44's Phase 4 confirmed for proj
#[sub] save).

app gtk_version

#[sub] === Phase 3: extra-args refusal (Branch B) ===

#[sub] Pass a positional argument the verb doesn't accept. The
#[sub] expected trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   > app gtk_version "extra"
#[sub]   error invoke threw: app gtk_version: expected zero arguments
#[sub]
#[sub] Operator-visual on the error message. Same shape as smoke 63's
#[sub] Phase 3 with the verb name swapped.

app gtk_version "extra"

#[sub] === Phase 4: unknown-verb refusal on the same singleton ===

#[sub] Address the singleton with a verb name that doesn't exist
#[sub] (`uptime` is a probe that might naturally arrive as a future
#[sub] verb but isn't one today; if added later, change this string
#[sub] to something still-not-defined). The expected trace line is:
#[sub]
#[sub]   > app uptime
#[sub]   error invoke threw: app: unknown verb 'uptime'
#[sub]
#[sub] Same unknown-verb fall-through as smoke 63's Phase 4;
#[sub] validates the dispatch shape is consistent across both verbs
#[sub] shipped in s263.

app uptime

#[sub] === Predicted observables ────────────────────────────────────────────

#[sub] Expected summary line:
#[sub]
#[sub]   4 lines, 0 pass, 0 fail, 2 error
#[sub]
#[sub] Second verb on the `app` singleton; no row tick (verbs-on-
#[sub] existing-singleton). Eleventh consumer of context_mask() in
#[sub] the corpus; registry-promotion clock at 10-11/n, still held by
#[sub] design.
